# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battle-of-scheveningen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The **Action of 29 January 1654** was a naval battle between small naval forces of the Dutch and the English, near either Bandar Abbas or Sindh.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Following the commencement of the First Anglo-Dutch War in December 1653, three English merchant ships, namely the *Falcon*, *Dove*, and *Welcome*, set sail from Diu with the purpose of proceeding to Gombroon to load cargo onto the *Endeavour*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Upon reaching the Persian Gulf these ships engaged two Dutch vessels in battle for a couple of hours.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Despite having a superior force, they eventually withdrew.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Subsequently, they set sail towards the *Endeavour*, which was being pursued by a Dutch fleet.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] They anchored at Gombroon Roads and remained there for two days.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] During the naval battle, the Dutch Admiral's ship was rendered ineffective by a broadside from the English ship *Welcome*, which had 21 cannons on that side.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The English ship *Falcon* initially collided with the Dutch Admiral's ship but was soon cleared, only to engage another Dutch ship and lose its foremast.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The *Falcon* was eventually boarded by the Dutch from the laden ship, resulting in an hour-long struggle with considerable losses on both sides.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] However, a groundless fear of a fire led the *Falcon'*s crew to abandon their ship and escape in boats, leaving behind over 60 able-bodied men who hadn't been injured.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The Welcome and the Dove managed to avoid significant harm during the battle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The *Endeavour*, although initially engaged with two Dutch ships, eventually sank after taking many shots under the waterline, resulting in the loss of English and Dutch lives.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The Dutch ships pursued the 2 retreating English ships later in the day.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The battle was poorly managed on both sides, with reports of drunkenness among the Dutch and likely similar conditions among the English.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The Welcome and the Dove safely reached Surat on February 9, 1653–4.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Two days later, two Dutch ships arrived at Surat, bringing the captured *Falcon* and about 80 English prisoners, which was seen as a dishonorable outcome for the English.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] After the battle, the English lodged a complaint about the Dutch attack with the Safavid authorities and requested assistance.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] However, their plea for aid was declined because the Safavid Empire was preoccupied with other pressing matters.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Moreover, the Safavids assured the English that they had no intention of taking action against the Dutch, primarily due to their substantial trade interests with the Dutch that they did not want to ruin.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] The Dutch dominance in the Gulf was so big that after this battle that the English Agent in Basrah received orders to relocate to a safer location.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] There was even consideration of sending silk bought in Persia to Europe via Isfahan.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] Fortunately, news of peace eventually put an end to this precarious situation.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/action-of-29-january-1654] This also destroyed England's ideas of an alliance with Portugal to expel the Dutch from India.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] The naval **Battle of Dover** , fought on 19 May 1652 (29 May 1652 Gregorian calendar), was the first engagement of the First Anglo-Dutch War between the navies of the Commonwealth of England and the United Provinces of the Netherlands.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] It proved to be an indecisive battle involving the flagships of Admirals Maarten Tromp and Robert Blake.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Opinions about the outcome of that battle vary among historians of that period.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] The English Parliament had passed the first of the Navigation Acts in October 1651, aimed at hampering the shipping of the highly trade-dependent Dutch.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Agitation among the Dutch merchants had been further increased by George Ayscue's capture in early 1652 of 27 Dutch ships trading with the royalist colony of Barbados in contravention of an embargo.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Prior to the battle, Oliver Cromwell had issued an ordinance requiring all foreign warships in the North Sea or English Channel to lower their flag in salute when encountering ships of the English navy.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Combined with Ayscue's seizure of the Dutch merchantmen trading with Barbados, this led to a rapid deterioration in Anglo-Dutch relations.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Tromp was subsequently given orders to protect Dutch commerce while keeping watch over the English navy.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] On 19 May 1652, Tromp was cruising in the English Channel with a fleet of forty ships between Nieuport and the mouth of the Meuse River.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] General at Sea Robert Blake was lying in Dover Roads with fifteen warships, with eight others were anchored in Bourne in the Downs.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] While on patrol, Tromp received orders from a dispatch ketch to attack Blake's fleet, and had not struck his flag in salute.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Blake, aboard his flagship *James*, assumed Tromp had received orders to commence battle and fired two warning shots.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] A defiant Tromp hoisted a red battle flag, which prompted *James* to fire a third shot, hitting Tromp's ship *Brederode* and wounding a number of its crew.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] This was followed with Tromp returning fire with a warning broadside from *Brederode*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] *James* in turn fired a broadside and a battle that would last five hours ensued.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Tromp immediately engaged Blake's flag ship where the two ships exchanged broadsides as they passed one another.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] While tacking to turn and fire another broadside, *Brederode* came into violent contact with *President*, which grappled with the *Brederode* and began boarding it.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] During the fierce melee that followed, Tromp's crew forced the attackers back on to their own ship.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] At this time, the English ship *Garland* came along to the other side of *Brederode*, placing it between *President* and *Garland*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Johan Evertsen, now aware of Tromp's plight, quickly came to assist, placing his ship directly alongside *President* and firing broadsides which severed all her masts, after which Evertsen's crew boarded her and engaged in hand-to-hand fighting before being beaten back.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] The fighting continued until nightfall, where both sides withdrew, the battle having no distinct victor.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] The ships of Tromp and Evertsen divided their prisoners between them and sailed back toward Texel, with Blake, with his flagship in tow making his way to Dover.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] Tromp then offered his excuses to Blake and asked for the return of the prize, but this was refused by Blake.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dover-1652] War was declared by the Commonwealth of England on 8 July 1652.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The naval **Battle of Dungeness** took place on 30 November 1652 (10 December in the Gregorian calendar) during the First Anglo-Dutch War near the cape of Dungeness in Kent.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] At the same time the largest English vessels remained in repair and active ships were undermanned as sailors deserted or rioted because their wages were in arrears.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] This left the English weakened and badly outnumbered in home waters.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Meanwhile, the Dutch were making every effort to reinforce their fleet.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Dutch trade interests demanded that their navy would make a final effort to convoy merchantmen to the south.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] At first, unfavourable southwestern gales forced him to return but on 23 November he again sailed south.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] After a council of war in which it was decided to avoid battle, the English promptly left their anchorage, sailing south.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake may not have realised how large the Dutch fleet was, or he may have feared to become trapped like the Spanish had been some years earlier in the Battle of the Downs.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The wind was now strong from the northwest, so the English could not return to the Downs in any case, having to settle for Dover.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The English fleet swiftly rounded South Foreland while the Dutch were unable to reach them, both fleets anchoring in the evening at about five miles distance.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] During the night a storm dispersed some Dutch vessels.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Next morning, at noon the two fleets began to move southwest, with the English hugging the coast and the Dutch keeping some distance.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The forces were separated by the Rip-Raps and the Varne Shoal and therefore unable to engage.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Ultimately the curve of the shoreline, the cape of Dungeness or the "Hook of the Shingles" jutting out, forced the English to turn on a southerly course.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Between the Varne Shoal and Dungeness a narrow exit exists.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake had hoped to escape through it but when he arrived about seventeen Dutch ships were already waiting for him.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Nevertheless, he continued his manoeuvre.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] At about 15:00, the leading ships of both fleets met in what a contemporary account called a "bounteous rhetoric of powder and bullet".
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake's *Triumph* was the first larger ship to sail through the exit.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] At that moment Tromp's *Brederode* arrived and the Dutch commander immediately hoisted the red "bloodflag" as a sign to attack.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake, noticing this, tacked to cross the bow of the *Brederode*, giving his opponent a broadside.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] In response, Tromp also tacked and fired a salvo.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The next English ship, the *Garland*, then moved between the *Triumph* and the *Brederode* in an attempt to cross the latter's bow also.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] This failed however, the *Garland* ramming the bow of the *Brederode* at starboard with such force that both ships remained entangled.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The snout and bowsprit of the *Brederode* broke off.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The larger crew of the *Brederode* swiftly boarded the *Garland*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Tromp encouraged his men by promising a reward of five hundred guilders to the first who would strike the English flag.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] One sailor climbed into the main mast of the *Garland* and replaced the St George's Cross with the Prince's Flag.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] In despair, captain Richard Batten blew up his own upper deck to drive away the Dutch.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Meanwhile, the third English ship to arrive, the *Anthony Bonaventure*, grappled the port of the *Brederode*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Covering the deck of the Dutch ship with canister shot, it soon forced its crew below deck.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Noticing the plight of his commander, Vice-Admiral Johan Evertsen in turn boarded the port of the *Anthony Bonaventure* with his *Hollandia*, so that four ships were now attached.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] In ferocious fighting his men, losing sixty, killed the entire crew of the *Anthony Bonaventure*, including Captain Walter Hoxton.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] When Tromp's secretary, standing next to him, was killed by a musket ball, he exhorted the combined crews of the *Brederode* and the *Hollandia* to assault the *Garland*, exclaiming "Children, things cannot go on this way.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The *Garland* was taken, with sixty killed out of a crew of one-hundred fifty, including Captain Batten.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] At this point the *Garland* was in a bad condition, her rudder largely having been shot away.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake tried to assist the *Garland* and the *Anthony Bonaventure* but was constantly attacked by Dutch flagships such as the *Princes Louise* of Johan de Liefde and the *Monnickendam* of Pieter Florisse.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The *Triumph* nearly avoided being grappled at both sides, by the *Princes Louise* and the *Gulden Beer* of Captain Jan de Haes.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake received little support from the remainder of the English fleet.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] When the *Happy Entrance* entered the channel, she was at once assaulted and only with difficulty managed to extract herself.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The other English ships began to understand the tactical situation: the exit functioned as a bottleneck and trying to force it would only allow the Dutch to overpower the English ships one by one.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] On the other hand, most Dutch ships did not engage either.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Annoyed, Commodore Michiel de Ruyter on the *Witte Lam* entered the exit in the opposite direction to attack the mass of the English ships but no one followed him and he was forced to withdraw.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] He complained in his journal: "If we had had any help, yea of but ten or twelve ships, we would have beaten the entire fleet".
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Despite the tactical difficulties, it was unacceptable to leave Blake to his fate.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The two most heavily armed English vessels apart from the *Triumph*, the *Vanguard* and the *Victory*, used their superior firepower to break the Dutch opposition and allowed Blake to retreat and join the English main force.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The *Triumph* had lost her fore-topmast and Blake had been wounded.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Around 17:00, the onset of darkness ended the battle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] A large part of the Dutch fleet had not even arrived yet.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The English fleet by nightfall had lost five ships.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] These included the captured *Garland* and *Anthony Bonaventure* that would be taken into Dutch service as the *Rozenkrans* and the *Bonaventura*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Two smaller vessels were burnt, one of them perhaps the light frigate *Acorn*, and one sunk.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] In the evening, the Dutch lost the *Schiedam*, also known as the *Gelderland* because the States of Gueldres had paid for her, through fire and subsequent explosion.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Captain Dirk Juinbol died from his wounds the next day.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake that night retreated under cover of darkness to his anchorage in the Downs.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The Dutch did not follow but used this time to repair the ships, especially the *Brederode*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The next morning the Dutch intercepted a group of three merchantmen sailing from the west.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Their guard ship, the *Merlin*, managed to escape, but they themselves were taken and their cargo of figs and lemons were distributed among the Dutch crews.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Tromp could not be satisfied with the result however as the Dutch had missed an opportunity to annihilate the English.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] On 1 December, he pursued Blake who, however, had already rounded South Foreland again.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The wind turned east, which allowed Blake to quickly reach the Thames but slowed the Dutch.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] A group of English ships was encountered, that had been sent to reinforce Blake but had sailed past him in the darkness.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Two new frigates, the *Ruby* and the *Sapphire*, managed to escape, but the *Hercules*, an armed merchantman, was run ashore by her captain, Zachary Browne.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Most of the crew fled inland and the *Hercules*, and Browne, were captured by the *Haes in 't Veld* of Bastiaan Centsen, who managed to refloat the vessel.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Returning to the Strait of Dover, Tromp allowed his merchant convoy to split up, each group of merchantmen continuing its way towards their individual destination together with their protecting warships.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Tromp considered attacking Blake in the Medway, but despite offering a reward of fifty Flemish pounds, in the entire Dutch fleet not a single pilot could be found who dared to navigate these dangerous waters.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Not until 1667 did De Ruyter manage to execute such an attack, in the Raid on the Medway.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The battle resulted in several reforms in the English Fleet.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Part of Blake's force consisted of impressed merchant vessels that retained their civilian captains/owners.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Many of them refused to participate in the battle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Some naval captains insisted on their traditional right to enter and leave the battle at times of their choosing, and to leave formation in order to secure any prize.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Blake threatened to resign if something was not done.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty responded by requiring all impressed vessels to be under the command of naval captains, and issuing Sailing and Fighting Instructions which significantly enhanced an admiral's authority over his fleet.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] The victory gave the Dutch temporary control of the English Channel and so control of merchant shipping.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] A legend says that Tromp attached a broom to his mast as a sign that he had swept the sea clean of his enemies, but in his book *The Command of the Ocean*, N.A.M.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Roger doubts the legend as such a boasting action would have been out of character for Tromp.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Additionally, at the time, a broom attached to a mast was the way of showing that a ship was for sale.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-dungeness] Also, Dutch contemporaneous sources make no mention of it.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The naval **Battle of Elba** (or **Battle of Monte Cristo**) was a naval battle which took place on 28 August 1652 during the First Anglo-Dutch War, between a Dutch squadron under Johan van Galen and an English squadron under Captain Richard Badiley.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The English were trying to reach Livorno, where a squadron under Captain Henry Appleton was under siege by the Dutch squadron.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] Leaving four of his fourteen vessels to maintain the watch over Livorno, van Galen took his remaining ten ships to intercept Badiley's squadron.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The two encountered each other between Montecristo and Elba Islands.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The *Phoenix* was captured by the *Jaarsveld*, while the other English warships retreated into Porto Longone.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The captured ship, *Phoenix*, was recaptured 2 months later during a night raid at Livorno.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The *Jaarsveld* and four other ships of the squadron belonged to the Amsterdam Admiralty, but the *Prinses Roijaal*, *Eendracht* and *Jonge Prins* belonged to the Noorderkwartier Admiralty, while *Wapen van Zeeland* and *Zeelandia* belonged to the Zeeland Admiralty.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-elba] The squadron was convoying four merchantmen, who however took no part in the Action and made their way independently into Porto Longone.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] The naval **Battle of Leghorn** took place on 4 March 1653 (14 March Gregorian calendar), during the First Anglo-Dutch War, near Leghorn (Livorno), Italy.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] It was a victory of a Dutch squadron under Commodore Johan van Galen over an English squadron under Captain Henry Appleton.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] Afterwards, another English squadron under Captain Richard Badiley, which Appleton had been trying to join up with, reached the scene in time to observe the capture of the last ships of Appleton's squadron, but was outnumbered and forced to return to Porto Longone.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] In 1652 the government of the Commonwealth of England, mistakenly believing that the United Provinces after their defeat at the Battle of the Kentish Knock would desist from bringing out fleets so late in the season, split their fleet between the Mediterranean and home waters.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] This division of forces led to a defeat at the Battle of Dungeness in December 1652, and by early 1653 the situation in the Mediterranean was critical too.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] Appleton's squadron of six ships (including four hired merchantmen) was trapped in Leghorn by a blockading Dutch fleet of 16 ships, while Richard Badiley's of eight (also including four hired merchantmen) was at Elba.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] The only hope for the English was to combine their forces, but Appleton sailed too soon and engaged with the Dutch before Badiley could come up to help.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] Three of his ships were captured and two destroyed and only one (*Mary*), sailing faster than the Dutch ships, escaped to join Badiley.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] Badiley engaged the Dutch, but was heavily outnumbered and retreated.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] The battle gave the Dutch command of the Mediterranean, placing the English trade with the Levant at their mercy, but Van Galen was mortally wounded, dying on 13 March.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] One of the Dutch captains at the battle was son of Lieutenant-Admiral Maarten Tromp, Cornelis Tromp, who was to become a famous admiral himself and one of the most celebrated and controversial figures in Dutch naval history due to his actions in the Anglo-Dutch Wars and the Scanian War.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] The *Eendracht* and *Jonge Prins* were ships of the Noorderkwartier Admiralty, all the others (including the hired merchantmen) pertained to the Amsterdam Admiralty.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] The fireship is listed as *Charity* in *Mariner's Mirror* vol.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] 49, but according to *Mariner's Mirror* vol.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-leghorn] 24 that ship was expended during an action off Plymouth on 27 August 1652.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The **Battle of Plymouth** was a naval battle in the First Anglo-Dutch War.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] It took place on 16 August 1652 (26 August 1652 (Gregorian calendar) and was a short battle, but had the unexpected outcome of a Dutch victory over England.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] General-at-Sea George Ayscue of the Commonwealth of England attacked an outward bound convoy of the Dutch Republic commanded by Vice-Commodore Michiel de Ruyter.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The two commanders had been personal friends before the war.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The Dutch were able to force Ayscue to break off the engagement, and the Dutch convoy sailed safely to the Atlantic while Ayscue sailed to Plymouth for repairs.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Around 10 August, De Ruyter took sea before the merchantmen had arrived, to seek out an English fleet of forty ships, commanded by Ayscue, which he knew had left The Downs on 19 July.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] De Ruyter's squadron at that moment consisted of 23 warships and six fireships, with a total of about 600 cannon and 1,700 men.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] As De Ruyter reported to the States-General of the Netherlands, most crews were badly trained, many ships poorly maintained and he had just two months of supplies.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Nevertheless, he preferred to give battle early without the burden of having to protect the convoy.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Reaching the English Channel, he soon discovered that Ayscue was not interested in fighting the Dutch squadron, but avoided it in the hope of intercepting the convoy.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] To lure Ayscue out De Ruyter started to cruise off the coast of Sussex, causing an uproar with the local population, but Ayscue, despite his fleet having grown to 42 ships, did not react.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Meanwhile, De Ruyter had lost two ships, sent out to escort a single incoming merchantman to the mouth of the Somme river, when they collided, sinking one, the *Sint Nicolaes*, and severely damaging the other, *Gelderlandt*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] On 11 August De Ruyter at last did rendezvous with the convoy of sixty merchantmen off Gravelines in the southern North Sea.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] He was pleased to notice that it brought ten warships with it, bringing his total to 31.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] On 13 August De Ruyter re-entered the Channel near Calais.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] His instructions were to escort the convoy to the Atlantic.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] There most ships would head for the Mediterranean together with their ten escorts, while the original squadron would have to wait to pick up merchantmen coming from the West Indies and transporting silver.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Ayscue's fleet had then grown to 47 vessels: 38 men-of-war, among which armed merchantmen; five fireships, and four smaller vessels.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] On 15 August, the English spotted the Dutch fleet off the coast of Plymouth and took sea.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Ayscue attempted a direct attack from the north the next day, off the coast of Brittany around 13:30, against the convoy, having the weather gauge.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] He hoped it would scatter, allowing him to capture some very profitable prizes, but De Ruyter unexpectedly separated his naval squadron and changed course to meet Ayscue's attack, shielding the merchantmen.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] They were now unable to form a line of battle and fully exploit their advantage in firepower over the Dutch.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The Dutch squadron however, sailing to the northwest, was in a rough defensive leeward line formation, with the Frisian acting Rear-Admiral Joris Pieterszoon van den Broeck commanding the van, De Ruyter himself commanding the centre and Dutch Rear-Admiral Jan Aertsen Verhoeff commanding the rear.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Around 16:00 the Dutch fleet and seven forward English vessels met and almost immediately passed through each other, both sides afterwards claiming to have "broken the enemy line".
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Having thus gained the weather gauge the Dutch at once exploited this by turning and attacking from the north.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] They would describe this as a second breaking of the line but probably the battle soon degenerated into a confusing mêlée.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] With their best ships now surrounded by the mass of Dutch vessels and bearing the brunt of the fight, the slower remainder of the English fleet, largely consisting of poorly trained hired merchantmen, was, reaching the scene of the battle, not overly zealous to get involved.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Their numerical superiority thus also gained the English little.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The largest Dutch vessel, the Dutch East India Company warship *Vogelstruys*, by Dutch standards heavily armed with a lower tier of 18-pounders, got separated from the rest of the Dutch fleet and was attacked by three English ships at once and boarded.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Her crew was close to surrendering when her captain, the Frisian Douwe Aukes, threatened to blow her up first.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Faced with this alternative the crew rallied, drove off the English boarding team and put up such a fight that the English vessels, much damaged and two even in a sinking condition, broke off the attack.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The Dutch employed their tactic of disabling enemy vessels by firing at their masts and rigging with chain shot.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] At the end of the afternoon Ayscue, feeling rather unsupported, decided to break off the unsuccessful engagement and to retreat to Plymouth to repair his ships before any became so damaged they would be captured.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The *Bonaventure* could only disengage after an English fireship, the *Charity* commanded by Captain Simon Orton, set itself alight and frightened off the attacking Dutch vessels.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Neither side lost a warship, but both sides suffered heavy casualties among their crews.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The Dutch had about sixty dead and fifty wounded.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The reports on the English losses differ: one set the number as high as seven hundred casualties including the wounded (most from the failed attack on the *Vogelstruys*), another mentioned 91 dead, among them Ayscue's flag captain Thomas Lisle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Rear-Admiral Michael Pack had a leg amputated and shortly afterwards died of the complications.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] De Ruyter pursued the English fleet after its retreat.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] On the morning of the next day both forces transpired to be still close to each other and he hoped by aggressively pursuing to capture some stragglers.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Several English ships were in tow and might well be abandoned if he pressed hard enough.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] However, Ayscue, fearing for his reputation, on 17 August convinced the English council of war to again give battle if necessary and brought his entire force safely back to Plymouth on 18 August.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] De Ruyter then sent two warships to escort the merchant fleet through the Channel to the Atlantic.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] For a while he considered trying to attack the enemy fleet at anchorage in Plymouth Sound, but in the end decided against it as he did not have the weather gauge.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Then hearing that General-at-Sea Robert Blake was sailing to the west with a superior force of 72, he chose to withdraw to the west and kept assembling incoming West Indies ships throughout September.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] On 15 September Blake had reached Portland and sent out a squadron of eighteen sail commanded by William Penn to intercept De Ruyter, but the latter escaped east along the French coast while Blake had been forced by a storm to seek shelter in Torbay.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] De Ruyter escorted twelve merchantmen safely to Calais on 22 September (2 October Gregorian calendar) when his supplies had nearly run out.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Shortly afterwards nine or ten of the Dutch ships, among them De Ruyter's flagship the *Kleine Neptunis*, then had to return to port for repairs, probably because of insufficiently repaired damage from the battle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The English ships had expected to easily defeat the Dutch in a set battle because of their superiority in armament and numbers.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] While the failure came as an unpleasant surprise to the English, the Dutch populace rejoiced in the tactical draw, hailing De Ruyter, who had not been well known among the larger public, as a naval hero.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] The English accused some merchantmen captains of cowardice.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Ayscue was blamed for poor leadership and organisation: his attempt to present the encounter as a victory failed to convince.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] He lost command after this battle, though probably for political reasons: he had known royalist sympathies.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Less important was his emphasis on capturing prizes while avoiding battle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] In the first year of the war this was a very common attitude, the English mainly seeing the conflict as one large privateering campaign, allowing them to gain riches at the expense of the Dutch; only with the Battle of the Gabbard would they really try to establish naval dominion.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] This victory was very important to the naval career of De Ruyter: it was the first time he commanded an independent force as a fleet commander.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] Before, he only had had subcommand of a flotilla aiding Portugal in 1641.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-plymouth-1652] As a result of the battle he acquired the nickname *The Sea Lion*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The First Anglo-Dutch War was caused by friction between the two naval powers of the century, competing for strategic supremacy over the world's merchant routes.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] England and the United Provinces had always been 'natural allies' against the Habsburgs, as deemed by the Council of State under the rule of Charles I.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] It has been argued that had Charles I stayed in power the war between the two nations would have never sprung, as he would never have obtained the necessary funding from parliament.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] However, the rise of the English Parliament under Oliver Cromwell saw the deterioration of diplomacy between the two as the Dutch stadtholder financially supported the Royalists.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Nonetheless, Cromwell did not challenge the Dutch, still consolidating his power at home.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] This changed when Parliamentary armies finally routed the Royalists at the Battle of Worcester, effectively ending the English Civil War.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] With Cromwell fully in power, the Parliament passed the Navigation Act 1651, requiring all goods destined to English ports to be transported by English ships, which impacted part of the Dutch ability to trade, since they were cut off from all of England's colonies in the Americas and elsewhere.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Later that year the Parliament gave an order which allowed privateers and warships to seize Dutch shipping.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Parliament began to enforce its sovereignty over the "British Seas", which granted the Royal Navy dominion from the North Sea to Cape Finisterre.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The translation of Parliament's words into action came when Sir George Ayscue folded Barbados into the Commonwealth and seized 27 Dutch merchantmen.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] This fleet was put under the command of Admiral Maarten Tromp, who had defeated the sixth and final Spanish Armada at the Battle of the Downs, 31 October 1639.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] That same year, the Dutch signed a treaty with Denmark with the intent to hurt English trade routs.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] War finally broke out after a confrontation between admirals Robert Blake and Maarten Tromp, May 1652, at the Battle of Dover.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Minor skirmishes followed at the Battle of Plymouth, the Battle of Elba, and the Battle of Kentish Knock.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The two fleets met for the first time in a major battle at the Battle of Dungeness, November 1652.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The battle turned out to be a failure for the English, forcing them to rethink their naval strategy, led by Admiral Sir Henry Vane and an Admiralty Committee, including developing a tactic that would mark naval warfare for the following century.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Taking a page out of the Dutch book the English reorganised each fleet into squadrons for greater tactical control.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] In fact, the tactic, renamed the line-of-battle tactic, would remain key to English/British naval strategy until the end of the Second World War.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The two fleets would meet again off Portland.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] During the first days of February 1653, Tromp escorted a convoy of merchant ships through the Channel and put them safely into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] He set to return to his home port, but first anchored off La Rochelle to repair and resupply his ships and waited for expected merchantmen coming from the Atlantic.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] He attempted to set sail on 20 February with 152 merchantmen, but was held back for three days by high winds and rough seas.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] On 24 February Tromp finally set sail, entering the area off Portland four days later where he spotted Blake's fleet attempting to cut them off.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Immediately, Tromp set the signal for a general attack and began the offensive with the wind in his favour as he had the weather gauge.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Tromp's flagship, *Brederode*, met Blake's flagship, *Triumph*, immediately, sending a broadside at mere metres distance.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Turning around, without having received a response from English gunners, he put a second broadside in *Triumph's* other side, and finally then delivered a third after turning around again.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Blake subsequently veered away and decided to fight at long range.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Dutch Commodore De Ruyter was able to attack the English rear and engaged the largest English vessel in the fleet, *Prosperity*, ending in a boarding attempt which was repulsed by the crew of the English vessel the first time around.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] A second boarding attempt forced the *Prosperity* to surrender thereafter, however.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] An attempt to reclaim the ship surrounded De Ruyter, but after an intense fight the Dutch commodore was able to fight his way out.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The battle continued for the day with heavy fire exchanged by both sides.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Later on 28 February Blake sent a squadron of frigates to intercept and claim the Dutch merchantmen off the coast of La Rochelle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Tromp quickly responded by sending his own captains to intercept the English.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Nonetheless, night brought a close to the day's battle.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The following day the English were the first to begin the engagement, with the wind in their favour.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The initiative of the English fleet was not gone from the previous day, but five attempts failed to break the Dutch line.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The day also saw 12 Dutch merchantmen caught by Blake's frigates after attempting to make a run for it, against Tromp's explicit orders.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] After the second day most of the Dutch warships were out of powder and shot, and there was none to resupply with.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The third day ended just the same, with a failure to break the Dutch line.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Several Dutch captains attempted to flee after completely running out of ammunition but Tromp ended their flight with a few shots across their ships.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The battle ended for the day when Blake drew off, after forcing the Dutch to fight to the point where they only had around half an hour worth of shot left.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Blake's reasoning for the disengagement has been attributed to the fact that he received a wound to the thigh that day.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] On the fourth day the English again attempted to resume action, but they found the sea empty of Dutch warships.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Tromp had guided the remainder of his fleet along the coastline, escaping certain defeat the next day, leaving 12 warships and a number of merchantmen behind.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] Although both sides claimed victory after the battle, the fact remains that it was Tromp who left the field, not Blake, and in the end, it was Blake who was able to commandeer 20 to 40 Dutch merchantmen and at least eight Dutch warships back to his homeport.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] The Battle of Portland restored English control over the English Channel.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] While Dutch propaganda tried to paint the battle as a Dutch victory or a "glorious defeat" and the populace publicly rejoiced at the heroism shown, Admiral Tromp and the other flag officers knew better, all coming home in an extremely dark mood.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] They concluded that the adoption of line tactics by the English would make it impossible for the Dutch to compensate inferior firepower with better seamanship and they urged the States-General to finally start building real heavy warships instead of replacing losses by recruiting armed merchants.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-portland] In an attempt to at least keep the North Sea open, an under-equipped Dutch fleet engaged the English again at the Battle of the Gabbard.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] The **Battle of Scheveningen** was the final naval battle of the First Anglo-Dutch War.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] It took place on 31 July 1653 between the fleets of the Commonwealth of England and the Dutch Republic.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] After their victory at the Battle of the Gabbard in June 1653, the English fleet of 120 ships under General at Sea George Monck on his flagship *Resolution* blockaded the Dutch coast, capturing many merchant vessels.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] The Dutch economy began to collapse, with mass unemployment and a severe economic downturn affecting it.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] On 24 July, Dutch Lieutenant-Admiral Maarten Tromp put to sea in *Brederode* with a fleet of 100 ships, to lift the blockade at the island of Texel, where Vice-Admiral Witte de With's 27 ships were blockaded by the English.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] The winds were fierce on 30 July and overnight, giving both fleets pause.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] Around 7:00 a.m. on 31 July, the Dutch gained an advantage from the weather and attacked, led by *Brederode*.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] The fleets moved through each other four times.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] Tromp was killed early in the fight by a sharpshooter in the rigging of Sir William Penn's ship.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] His death was kept secret to keep up the morale of the Dutch but by late afternoon, twelve of their ships had either been sunk or captured and many were too damaged to continue the fight.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] In the end, morale broke and a large group of vessels under the command of merchant captains fled to the north.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] De With tried to halt their flight but had to limit himself to covering the retreat to the island of Texel.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] The English fleet was also badly damaged and with many wounded in urgent need of treatment, returned to port to refit and were unable to maintain the blockade.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] Both sides claimed a victory: the English because of their tactical superiority, the Dutch because the strategic goal of their attack, the lifting of the blockade, had been achieved.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] Peace negotiations began in earnest, leading to the 1654 Treaty of Westminster.
[src:battle-of-scheveningen/battle-of-scheveningen] The damage done to the Dutch fleet effectively ended the first war.
